4.75/5  rDev +7.5%look: 4.75 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 4.75On tap at the brewery. Pours classic RIS: opaque black with a dark tan head. Smell is amazing, with a rich combo of chocolate and coffee, and tons of cherries and other ripe, dark fruit I can't quite place. Taste is complex progression of what's on the nose, and is just super delicious. Many layers of flavor. Fairly sweet, but with an offsetting bitterness that is nearly perfect for the style. A huge, rich beer that is masterfully constructed. One of the best RIS beers I've ever had. 488 charactersBeers-es, Dec 14, 2015
4/5  rDev -9.5%look: 4 | smell: 4 | taste: 4 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4italianstallion, Dec 14, 2015
4.47/5  rDev +1.1%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 4.52013 bottle from notes from yesterday's share.
This beer was probably the most gorgeous pour of our share, with a thick and pitch black pour that turned into a small to average sized head quickly. The head was a chocolatey brown in color with good retention and very good lacing. When I took a sniff of the beer, the hops were definitely still in there. Upfront, the hops very still mildly bitter and melded with the dark and burnt malts. The back half of the scent was mostly semi-sweet, fudgey chocolate. When the first sip hits the tongue, the same flavor arc that happened in the scent starts, with a mild hop bitterness that transitions into a sweet, chocolate flavor in the middle of the drink. On the back half of the drink, the primary flavor is a chocolate-hops combo platter with a touch of dark fruits. The mouthfeel of this one is thick and smooth with a certain amount of creaminess. The carbonation is very low and the alcohol is very well hidden.
Overall, this is a phenomenal beer. In this case, ~2 years in the bottle has turned it from a hoppy stout into a delicious mix of hoppy and chocolate flavors. 1,122 charactersboilermakerbrew, Dec 13, 2015
