4.35/5  rDev -1.6%look: 4 | smell: 4 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5Had this at a stout night (9 July, 2011) with friends. It was Ivan, Abyss, Darkness, and Dark Lord, in that order. We had pretzels and water and some Goose Island Summertime in between rounds. Everything I had was out of a 6 oz snifter.
This pours a thick-looking black with a dark, short head that left some lace on the way down, something I was not expecting at all. On the nose I could tell that this was going to be a bitter affair, with big quantities of roasted barley and pine hops, which probably have begun to fade but still have a presence. There was also some molasses and bitter chocolate. In the mouth all of these flavors meld into something amazing. There is no disconnect. From the lowest notes of molasses and barley to the highest bits of chocolate, there are no gaps. The body was huge, not syrupy but towards a milkshake, with some warmth emerging as it warms up. The finish is ultra long, the bitter notes sticking around a bit longer than the sweet molasses.
Overall, this was probably my favorite beer of the night. Everything just blended together pretty nicely into one of my favorite stouts. I'm pretty sure I'll get to revisit all of the others at some point, but this is probably the only chance I had with Darkness. It was an amazing one. 1,269 charactersEricCioe, Jul 21, 2011
